[1] Indonesia, Papua: suspicions denied
Date: Thu, 30 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Postcourier.com (PNG), 27 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.postcourier.com.pg/20060327/mohome.htm>

There has been no reported case of bird flu in the Papua Province on the
Indonesia side of the border, says the National Agriculture Quarantine and
Inspection Authority (NAQIA). Slamming a Post-Courier front page story on
Thursday [23 Mar 2006] that alleged the outbreak of the deadly bird flu
virus in Papua's Timika area, NAQIA managing director Andrew Yamanea said
the closest bird flu case reported was in South Sulawesi and the article
was ill-informed and unverified.
He said classical swine fever (hog cholera) was the only animal-born
disease recently reported in Timika which could have been mistaken for the
bird flu virus. "The closest bird flu-infected province in Indonesia to
Papua is South Sulawesi in the east and quite far from PNG," Mr Yamanea
said. "There is, however, confirmation of classical swine fever (hog
cholera) cases in Timika area in Papua Province that we are aware of. Hog
cholera is predominately a pig disease and does not affect humans but is a
serious fatal disease in pigs and can spread very rapidly within a pig
population. NAQIA has already issued alert notices for this disease to its
officers on the ground. This could be the disease that has been confused
with bird flu in the Post-Courier report. NAQIA has in place surveillance
and monitoring system in PNG and disease information networking system with
neighbouring countries and regional animal health organisation to be
well-informed of the animal disease situations in the region, including
Papua Province."
The NAQIA will conduct joint public awareness campaigns with the Health
Department and the OK Tedi Mining Limited (OTML) in areas identified as
high risks, especially those located close to a national border such as
Sandaun Province.
Mr Yamanea, who stressed that the authority was mindful of the bird flu
virus threat as well as plant- and animalborne diseases, urged public
servants and local communities to report cases of animals or plants dying
mysteriously. "NAQIA has also issued instructions and distributed disease
information sheets and posters for target diseases under surveillance to
NAQIA and DPI offices in the border provinces to alert communities in these
areas to take necessary measures," he said.
NAQIA is collaborating with the Health Department and the World Health
Organisation's PNG office to develop a pandemic emergency preparedness plan
for the country. But the Post-Courier report's writer Ian Kakarere, and the
source of his story, NAQIA's Kiunga officer Kaiki Namalu, refused to back
down from their story.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to Indonesia's last report to the OIE, sent on 6 Jan 2006, the
following main regions had been affected by avian influenza: Nanggroe Aceh
Darussalam; Bali Badung; Jakarta South; Jambi Sarolangun; West Jawa;
Central Jawa; Lampung Bandar; West Lampung; Lampung Tangamus; Lampung
Tulang; Riau Dumai; South Sulawesi; South-east Sulawesi; West Sulawesi;
South Selatan; North Sumatra; Yogyakarta. Administrative map at
<http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/db/Indonesia_provinces_english.png>.
The alleged confusion between avian influenza and swine fever, 2 quite
different disease entities, is not easy to explain. A fresh update from
Indonesia's veterinary authorities would help to clarify the situation. -
Mod.AS]
